In your case, there are two different problems that need to be solved: the Spring for GraphQL auto-detection of schema files, and the IntelliJ IDEA plugin support.

First, if you&#39;ve structured your application this way, you should tell Spring Boot to [look for schema files in the entire classpath][1] with a configuration property:

```properties
spring.graphql.schema.locations=&quot;classpath*:graphql/**/&quot;
```

Second, the IntelliJ IDEA plugin for GraphQL support is relying on [the `.graphqlconfig` specification][2]. In your case, you could add a `.graphqlconfig` file at the root of your project with the following:

```json
{
  &quot;projects&quot;: {
    &quot;shared&quot;: {
      &quot;includes&quot;: [&quot;./shared/src/main/resources/graphql/*.graphql&quot;]
    },
    &quot;user&quot;: {
      &quot;includes&quot;: [&quot;./user/src/main/resources/graphql/*.graphql&quot;]
    },
    &quot;task&quot;: {
      &quot;includes&quot;: [&quot;./task/src/main/resources/graphql/*.graphql&quot;]
    }
  }
}

```

You can [check out the plugin documentation][3] since there are multiple ways to structure your configuration for this use case.


